IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
INCIDENT WAS RECORDED ON WALMART DRIVER’S DASH CAMERA, VERBAL STATEMENTS FROM ALL WITNESSES WERE RECORDED ON BODY WORN CAMERA.

NEIGHBORHOOD CHECK:
Due to the nature of the incident, no neighborhood check was conducted.

PARTIES INVOLVED:
Maurice Logan Mitchell (B/M DOB: 01/29/1981)

Shaniqua Octavia Mitchell (B/F DOB: 01/02/1991)

Jeremy Lynn Crawford (B/M DOB: 01/01/1984)

Dionte Anthony Coates (B/M DOB: 06/04/1966)

Jervado Antonio Carrington (B/M DOB: 11/23/1994)

SCENE PROCESSING:
            Trooper Bryan Peris, and I TFC Strine observed blood drippings from the rear driver’s side door down to the driver’s side rear tire. Upon opening the driver side rear door, additional blood was located within the rear seat of the vehicle. Trooper Peris and I briefly entered the suspect’s vehicle to view the suspect’s suicide note left within the vehicle. Upon realizing the nature of the incident, the vehicle was immediately secured and blocked off by yellow police tape.
             Sgt. Zarzecki of the Maryland State Police CRASH team responded to the scene. Sgt. Zarzecki mapped and photographed the scene in its entirety, and the vehicle was later transported to the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack for Annapolis Police Department to complete a search warrant. At approximately 2215 hours I made contact with Officers from the Annapolis Police Department, and gave them custody of all the suspects’ belongings that were recovered from his person or the scene. All items were logged on MSP 67’s per MSP policy. Annapolis Police Department executed a search warrant on the vehicle and began documenting and processing the vehicle.

NARRATIVE:
          At approximately 1354 hours, the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack was notified of an ongoing vehicle pursuit from Anne Arundel County Police Department, advising they were in pursuit of a stabbing suspect who had fled the scene of the crime in a white BMW. The pursuit was terminated due to losing sight of the suspect vehicle prior to the Bowie exit on westbound US 50. Later, the same day, at approximately 1616 hour Trooper Bryan Peris #7511 was traveling on eastbound on US 50 in the area of Lottsford Vista Rd, when he observed a white BMW on the right shoulder, and a Walmart Tractor Trailer combination stopped in lane 4 of eastbound US 50 east of Lottsford Vista Rd.
            Trooper Peris called over the radio and advised he then observed a black male lying in the roadway, while a passerby had stopped to begin administering CPR on the male who was lying in the roadway unresponsive. I, Trooper First Class Strine #6972, quickly arrived on scene and observed the white BMW on the right shoulder bearing Maryland tag “6EW5765”. I observed the vehicle had what appeared to be blood dripping around the rear driver side area of the vehicle. I applied latex gloves and approached the male who was lying in the roadway. EMS had arrived on scene and began attempting life saving measures on the male before transporting him to Capital Regional Trauma Center. The male was identified as Maurice Logan Mitchell (B/M DOB: 01/29/1981) by his Maryland driver's license.
            I began attempting to take statements from all citizens on scene, and all unnecessary parties on scene were told to vacate the scene for the investigation. I asked Jervado Antonio Carrington to begin filling out a written statement, and also proceeded to the Truck driver who was identified as Jeremy Lynn Crawford (B/M DOB: 01/01/1984) asking him to begin filling out a written statement. As Crawford began writing a statement, he became very emotional and advised he did not think he could do it. I asked him if he could give me a verbal statement which he was able to do, and this statement was captured on body worn camera.   
Trooper Peris advised he saw a handwritten note that was put in the front windshield of the white BMW which stated the subject’s name, and that he had attempted to kill his wife Shaniqua Octavia Mitchell, and was written in the fashion of a suicide note. I immediately had the vehicle secured with police tape and advised we would need to continue to have lanes two through four shut down pending the aide and assistance of the appropriate units. Due to Crawford becoming very emotional from the traumatic incident, I spoke with Officer First Class Christopher Parker Sr. of the Maryland Natural Resources Police, who advised they have a Crisis Management Team that could be called for the parties involved. I advised him that I believed it would be good for Crawford to have the Crisis Team started to speak with him about the incident.
            Trooper Peris proceeded to Capital Regional Trauma Center, and at approximately 1659 hours, Maurice Logan Mitchell was pronounced deceased by Capital Regional Medical Staff from the incident. The investigation was now being handled as a Suicide due to the verbal statements given by witnesses and the nature of the letter found inside the vehicle. Sgt. Kevin Zarzecki #6202 of the Maryland State Police CRASH team responded to the scene to assist me with the investigation. Sgt. Zarzecki mapped and photographed the scene, as well as completing a full walkthrough of the scene on body camera.
While Sgt. Zarzecki was mapping the scene, I made contact with Dionte Anthony Coates, who was the passerby that stopped and began chest compressions on Mitchell until EMS arrived. I then asked him for a verbal statement of what happened which was captured on body worn camera. Coates stated he did not see the incident occur, but Crawford and Carrington’s statements were both consistent in explaining that Mitchell appeared to have purposely jumped in front of the moving tractor trailer. Myrissa Ramie, and Randell Fisher Sr. of iMind Behavior Health responded to the scene and began speaking with Crawford and the remaining witnesses on scene.
            Upon completion of mapping the scene, I called a tow for the white BMW. Central Towing arrived on scene and the vehicle was stored at the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack for evidence and processing by the Annapolis Police Department for the attempted homicide investigation. I followed the tow truck with the vehicle from the scene back to the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack, where it was stored in our fenced in bullpen at approximately 2006 hours, awaiting the execution of a search warrant from Annapolis Police Department.  

            All events occurred in Prince George’s and Anne Arundel Counties.

            I request this case be closed due to the death of the at fault party    .

Crime Scene Mapping Supplement




Section I. - Narrative

On Monday, May 1, 2023, at approximately 1615 hours, Troopers from the MSP College Park Barrack responded to an initial report of a collision involving a pedestrian and a commercial vehicle. It was reported that the incident occurred on the eastbound side of the John Hanson Highway (US 50), east of Martin Luther King Jr. Highway (MD 704), Prince George's County, Maryland. Upon Trooper Jason Strine's (Advanced Collision Investigator) arrival, he observed the following vehicles and people:
  • Pedestrian/deceased - Maurice Logan Mitchell (DOB: 01/29/1981), of Annapolis, Maryland
  • Vehicle #1 - 2020 Freightliner truck tractor displaying Oklahoma registration 3EB222 pulling a 2023 semitrailer displaying Indiana registration PB30378 / Walmart Transportation LLC / USDOT # 063585
    • Driver - Jeremy Lynn Crawford (DOB: 01/01/1984), of Bear, Delaware
  • Pedestrian's vehicle (not involved in this incident) - 2010 BMW X5 displaying MD registration 6EW5765 registered to Shaniqua Octavia Mitchell, of Annapolis, Maryland
While Trooper Strine was conducting his scene investigation, he observed a suicide note in the BMW and suspected blood on the exterior and interior of the BMW. The suicide note included a confession from Maurice Mitchell that he attempted to kill his wife, Shaniqua Mitchell (registered owner of the BMW). Based upon the scene evidence and the totality of the circumstances, it was determined that this incident was a suicide and not a motor vehicle collision. 

Trooper Strine notified me of the above facts and I responded as requested. I contacted Maryland State Police Headquarters and advised to have the Maryland State Police Homicide Unit to contact me as well as investigators from the Criminal Enforcement Division. I made contact with the Maryland State Police Homicide Unit, and it was learned that the Maurice Mitchell was the suspect of an attempted homicide earlier that afternoon in Annapolis, Maryland and that the Annapolis Police Department was conducting that investigation (APD case number 23-10954). The Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division was contacted by the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack, and it was determined that TFC Strine would be completing the Criminal Investigation Report for the suicide.

Upon my arrival to the scene, I made contact with Detective Courtney Moore (Annapolis Police Department) who was the lead investigator for the attempted homicide and arrived on the scene the same time I did. I was tasked to document the scene with digital photography utilizing my agency-issued digital camera. Additionally, I was tasked with forensically mapping the crime scene utilizing my agency-issued Emlid Reach RS+ Global Positioning System (GPS) total station. The following supplement report documents my findings as part of the investigation and assistance to Trooper Strine and Detective Moore. 
 
Section II. - Investigation

After I completed documenting the scene with digital photography, I began to forensically map the crime scene utilizing my agency-issued Emlid Reach RS+ GPS total station. During the mapping, the Emlid Reach RS+ Base and Rover were connected. The solution status was "FIX" and "FLOAT", with the majority of data points resolution status "FLOAT". The coordinate system used was North American Datum (NAD83) Maryland (ftUS). NAD83 is a geocentric datum and geographical coordinate system based on the 1980 Geodetic Reference System ellipsoid (GRS80), which is mainly used in North America. It's measurements are obtained from both terrestrial and satellite data. A total of 49 GPS data points were collected. Of the 49 GPS data points collected, 11 data points had a solution status of "FIX" and 38 data points had a solution status of "FLOAT". 
 
Section III. - Diagram Creation

On Wednesday, June 7, 2023, I created a scaled diagram utilizing the comma-separated values (CSV) file. The CSV file was imported into Faro Zone computer aided design software to create the scaled diagram. The scaled diagram was saved in PDF and .FAR formats. 
 
Section IV. - Incident Dynamics

The following incident dynamics were determined based upon the scene evidence, totality of the circumstances, from other investigators, and confirmed via dash camera footage.

Investigation revealed that Maurice Mitchell was the suspect for the attempted homicide which occurred at the residence of both Maurice Mitchell and Shaniqua Mitchell on Monday, May 1, 2023, at approximately 1346 hours. The victim of the attempted homicide was Maurice Mitchell's wife, Shaniqua Mitchell. Earlier in the afternoon, APD attempted to conduct a stop of the BMW, but the possible pursuit was terminated on the westbound side of the John Hanson Highway (US 50), at the Prince George's County line.

On Monday, May 1, 2023, at approximately 1615 hours, the Maurice Mitchell parked the BMW on the right shoulder (off of the travel portion of the roadway) on the eastbound side of US 50, east of MD 704 and exited the vehicle and left the suicide note on the dashboard. The Freightliner was traveling east on US 50, east of MD 704 in lane number 4. The Maurice Mitchell, the pedestrian, walked directly in the path of travel of the Freightliner. The front of the Freightliner struck Maurice Mitchell in lane number 4, causing Maurice Mitchell to be projected forward onto the asphalt surface. 
 
Section V. - Review of the Autopsy Report

On Wednesday, June 7, 2023, at approximately 1142 hours, I received an electronic copy of the autopsy report from the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (OCME). 

Maurice Mitchell was pronounced on Monday, May 1, 2023, at 1659 hours, by hospital staff at the University of Maryland Capital Region Medical Center located in Largo, Maryland. 

The autopsy was conducted on Tuesday, May 2, 2023, at approximately 0900 hours, by Dr. Diana Nointin, Assistant Medical Examiner. The OCME case number was 23-05485. The cause of death was listed as multiple injuries and the manner of death was determined to be "suicide". Dr. Nointin opined that Maurice Mitchell died of multiple injuries sustained as a pedestrian struck by a motor vehicle. She noted that the investigation was consisted with a self-inflicted injury. The manner of death was suicide. Postmortem toxicology testing was negative for drugs and alcohol. 
 
Section VI. - Attachments that were included in for this report:

The following items were attached to this report: 
  • Autopsy Report
  • Diagram, drawn to scale
The following photographs have been uploaded into the VeriPic Digital Evidence System:
  • 92 digital photographs taken of the crime scene utilizing my agency-issued digital camera
The following items have been archived in the Crash Team files
  • 92 digital photographs
  • .FAR diagram file
Conclusion:

Upon approval, this supplement report will be provided to Trooper Strine and Detective Moore to utilize in their respective investigations. Any further investigation by this investigator will be captured under a separate supplement report.
